2093D - Skibidi Table
Note that there are $$$4$$$ possible positions of the cell and the values within it:
$$$x,y \le 2^{n-1} \Leftrightarrow d \le 2^{2n-2}$$$;
$$$x,y  \gt  2^{n-1} \Leftrightarrow 2^{2n-2}  \lt  d \le 2 \cdot 2^{2n-2}$$$;
$$$x  \gt  2^{n-1}, y \le 2^{n-1} \Leftrightarrow 2 \cdot 2^{2n-2}  \lt  d \le 3 \cdot 2^{2n-2}$$$;
$$$x \le 2^{n-1}, y  \gt  2^{n-1} \Leftrightarrow 3 \cdot 2^{2n-2}  \lt  d \le 4 \cdot 2^{2n-2}$$$.
Since all square tables of size $$$2^{n-1} \times 2^{n-1}$$$ are filled recursively, it is possible to find the corresponding value for the coordinate or the corresponding coordinate for the value depending on the query, add the required value to the answer, subtract the necessary value from the query, and transition from $$$n$$$ to $$$n-1$$$. This process can continue to reduce $$$n$$$ to one to handle the table manually, or to zero to immediately add to the answer $$$x = 1, y = 1, d = 1$$$.
This can be implemented either with a recursive function, or by subtracting the necessary powers of two, or by integer division of the coordinates by $$$2$$$ and the value by $$$4$$$, or by analyzing the bits in the binary representation of $$$x-1, y-1$$$, and $$$d-1$$$, or through a kind of binary search. Each of these solutions answers one query in $$$O(n)$$$.
